<DOC><DOCNO> AP890114-0113 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-01-14-89 1756EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     01-14 0419</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0428</SECOND><HEAD>Freezing Rain Across Lower Ohio Valley</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Freezing rain and sleet hindered motorists across the lower OhioValley Saturday, while snow fell from Missouri to Illinois.   Numerous traffic accidents were reported throughout the lowerOhio Valley as freezing rain slickened roads. Fifteen accidentsoccurred within a few minutes in Charleston, W.Va., and some roadswere closed in northeast Georgia because of slick conditions.   Snow fell from west-central Missouri to west-central IllinoisSaturday morning. The heaviest snowfall was over south-centralMissouri, where Columbia received 4 inches.   Elsewhere, snow continued to fall over the Cascade Mountains inthe Pacific Northwest and heavy rainfall was expected to createflooding problems in portions of western Tennessee and south-centralKentucky due to the already saturated ground and swollen streamsfrom previous rainfall.   Three inches of snow fell on the coastal mountains of Oregon and2 inches accumulated in western Washington.   Rain was falling from western Tennessee to the Mississippi GulfCoast. Flash flood watches were posted for the western two-thirds ofTennessee and for south-central Kentucky.   A cold front moving across the northern Plains and centralRockies was producing gusty winds as it passed. Snow showers werealso occurring behind this front in North Dakota, reducingvisibility to near zero across parts of north-central North Dakota.   In Norman, Okla., snowfall totaled up to 8{ inches.   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 14degrees below zero at Gunnison, Colo., to 85 degrees at Fort Myers,Fla. The low in the nation Saturday morning was 35 degrees belowzero at Gunnison, Colo.   Sunday's forecast called for rain from Alabama across thesouthern and mid-Atlantic states into southern New England; amixture of snow, rain and freezing rain from northeast New York tosouthern Maine; snow over the rest of Maine; rain along the northernPacific coast; snow in the northern intermountain region of thePacific Northwest; and strong and gusty winds in the northernRockies.   High temperatures were forecast in the teens and 20s in thecentral Rockies and from the northern Plains across the upperMississippi Valley to northern portions of the upper Great Lakes; inthe 50s and 60s along the California coast as well as from southernCalifornia across southern Arizona and New Mexico, parts of Texasand the lower Mississippi Valley and Alabama to the middle andsouthern Atlantic coast; in the 70s over much of the FloridaPeninsula; and in the 30s and 40s through the rest of the nation.</TEXT></DOC>